Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: Dangote Cement, Kenya Commercial Bank Are Active

-- B y   C h r i s   K a y
-- 
2011-04-13T15:52:23Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-13/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-kenya-commercial-bank-safaricom-move.html
The Ghana Stock Exchange Composite
Index fell 1.2 percent to 1,040.80 by the 3 p.m. close in Accra,
the lowest since March 3.  Kenya’s All-Share Index snapped three days of gains,
slumping 1.3 percent to 74.12 by the 3 p.m. close in Nairobi,
the most since March 21. The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share
Index rose for a second day, adding 0.5 percent to 24,816.67 by
the 2:30 p.m. close in Lagos, according to a statement on the
bourse’s website. Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index climbed 0.5 percent
to 2,047.60 at the 1:30 p.m. close in Port Louis, the highest
since Feb. 21. Namibia’s FTSE/ Namibia Overall Index (FTN098)  declined 0.1
percent to 875.93 by the 4 p.m. close in Windhoek.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Dangote Cement Plc (DANGCEM)  , Africa’s biggest producer
of the building material and  Nigeria ’s largest traded company,
retreated for the first time in 13 days, losing 2.5 naira, or 2
percent, 123 naira, after announcing plans to invest $3.9
billion constructing plants in countries including Ethiopia,
 Tanzania , the Democratic Republic of Congo and Gabon.  “Investors are waiting for more news and explanations on”
whether the units will report separately or if it will remain a
consolidated company, Dare Fajimolu, a Lagos-based cement
analyst with CSL Stockbrokers Ltd., said by phone today.        Kenya Commercial Bank Ltd. (KNCB)  , the nation’s biggest
lender by outlets, gained for a fifth day, adding 25 cents, or 1
percent, to 26.25 shillings, the highest price since September
2008, as it appointed 500 agents to provide banking services
across East Africa’s largest economy.  Safaricom Ltd. (SAFCOM)  , East Africa’s biggest mobile-
phone company, advanced 5 cents, or 1.2 percent, to 4.1
shillings, the biggest gain in almost a week, after saying it
signed an agreement with the Kenyan Bankers Association on data
provision to help speed up check-clearance times.  To contact the reporter on this story:
